r, Bozidar, Branko, Dragan, Dragana, Dragica, Dragomir, Branislav, Janek, Milan, Mirko, Radmila.","Serbian and Croatian (<b>Ilić</b>): patronymic from the personal name <i>Ilija</i>, an equivalent of   Elias  . Compare   Ilich   and   Elich  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Leich was born in 1547, in Kingsteignton, Devon, England, United Kingdom, his father, Richard Leich, was -279 and his mother, Mary Hope, was -280. He married Joyce Gravener about 1568, in Kingsteignton, Devon, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died in 1632, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 85."},"et":{"1547–1632":"1547–1632","1550–Female":"1550–Surnud","1569–1664":"1569–1664","1572–Male":"1572–Surnud","1827–Male":"1827–Surnud","1828–Female":"1828–Surnud","1547":"1547","1569":"1569","1632":"1632","ABT 1572":"umbes 1572","1664":"1664","Abt 1568":"umbes 1568","1572":"1572","1550":"1550","1828":"1828","1827":"1827","Worcestershire, England":"Worcestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom",", , , England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Kingsteignton, Teignbridge, Devonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Kingsteignton, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Kingsteignton, Devon, Engl